00:35:39.130 --> 00:35:42.560
to run two apps on the screen at
the same time in a split screen

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:43.730
mode.

00:35:43.730 --> 00:35:46.520
It also gives enhanced
notifications.

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:49.790
And by this, I mean
we now support actions

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:51.582
in a standard way within
the notifications,

00:35:51.582 --> 00:35:53.873
it's easier than ever for
developers to change the look

00:35:53.873 --> 00:35:56.810
and feel of these notifications,
and related notifications are

00:35:56.810 --> 00:36:00.055
bundled together with NuGet.

00:36:00.055 --> 00:36:02.180
I also want to talk to you
about enhanced DOS mode.

00:36:02.180 --> 00:36:05.910
So in Marshmallow, we introduced
something called DOS mode,

00:36:05.910 --> 00:36:08.570
which is a low power state.

00:36:08.570 --> 00:36:11.420
When the device's
screen is off and it's

00:36:11.420 --> 00:36:15.320
laying flat on a table, we
enter this special DOS mode

00:36:15.320 --> 00:36:17.110
that saves battery.

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:19.670
And with NuGet get we're
extending it further,

00:36:19.670 --> 00:36:23.450
so that when the screen is off
but the device is in motion,

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:29.030
like in your pocket, we
trigger this low battery state.

00:36:29.030 --> 00:36:31.790
And finally, NuGet
includes Vulkan,

00:36:31.790 --> 00:36:33.820
which is a new,
industry standard,

00:36:33.820 --> 00:36:37.840
low level graphics API that
delivers advanced performance

00:36:37.840 --> 00:36:38.800
on the latest hardware.

00:36:42.830 --> 00:36:45.830
NuGet also introduces
another major feature

00:36:45.830 --> 00:36:49.520
I want to tell you about-- VR.

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:51.290
So we've been playing
with VR for a while.

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:53.750
Two years ago we launched
Google Cardboard,

00:36:53.750 --> 00:36:57.050
and it's done a fantastic
job at giving people

00:36:57.050 --> 00:37:01.040
a taste of what VR can be like
through short form experiences

00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:05.000
that work on iOS and Android.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:08.140
And frankly, the adoption
and success of Cardboard

00:37:08.140 --> 00:37:11.270
has surpassed our expectations.

00:37:11.270 --> 00:37:14.710
So with NuGet, we're
introducing a new platform

00:37:14.710 --> 00:37:16.960
that we call
Daydream, that takes

00:37:16.960 --> 00:37:20.510
our vision of
affordable, ubiquitous VR

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:22.800
to the next level.

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:27.130
Daydream is comprised
of three key elements.

00:37:27.130 --> 00:37:31.250
It introduces a standard
for new Android handsets

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:35.330
that ensures that they can
deliver immersive, high quality

00:37:35.330 --> 00:37:38.370
VR experiences.

00:37:38.370 --> 00:37:42.610
It also includes a reference
design for a high quality VR

00:37:42.610 --> 00:37:47.750
headset that's powered
by a Daydream handset,

00:37:47.750 --> 00:37:50.380
and it includes a
reference design

00:37:50.380 --> 00:37:54.440
for-- we call it
positionally aware controller

00:37:54.440 --> 00:37:56.840
that knows where it
is, and that users

00:37:56.840 --> 00:38:02.720
can use to engage in these
immersive virtual environments.

00:38:02.720 --> 00:38:06.050
We launched the first
Daydream compatible device,

00:38:06.050 --> 00:38:10.790
the Pixel Phone by Google,
earlier this year in the fall.

00:38:10.790 --> 00:38:14.120
And we also launched
our own Daydream headset

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:15.910
and controller.

