00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:53.380
core.

00:45:53.380 --> 00:45:55.240
The core API has
provided a foundation

00:45:55.240 --> 00:45:57.300
that you need to build all apps.

00:45:57.300 --> 00:46:01.510
Angular's core APIs include
declarative templating that

00:46:01.510 --> 00:46:04.280
allows you to use standard
HTML and Angular markup

00:46:04.280 --> 00:46:07.490
to create powerful
UIs, automatic change

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:10.570
detection, dependency
injection improved

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:14.300
from our pioneering
implementation in Angular 1,

00:46:14.300 --> 00:46:17.080
an intuitive component model
that allows you to structure

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:19.090
your apps with
reusable architecture

00:46:19.090 --> 00:46:21.510
and natural separation
of concerns,

00:46:21.510 --> 00:46:25.330
and our new compiler, which
is capable of static analysis,

00:46:25.330 --> 00:46:29.080
giving you not only small
and fast apps, but also

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:33.340
improved error messaging
and automatic refactoring,

00:46:33.340 --> 00:46:36.610
the ability to swap
renderers, so you get true Dom

00:46:36.610 --> 00:46:40.870
independence, and you can target
platforms where no Dom exists.

00:46:40.870 --> 00:46:44.320
And this is really
critical for mobile.

00:46:44.320 --> 00:46:46.474
Beyond these foundational
building blocks.

00:46:46.474 --> 00:46:47.890
There are many
more things that we

00:46:47.890 --> 00:46:49.720
know most applications
will need,

00:46:49.720 --> 00:46:52.870
for example, UI components.

00:46:52.870 --> 00:46:55.360
We knew that we could make
developers more productive

00:46:55.360 --> 00:46:57.770
by providing APIs
for these use cases.

00:46:57.770 --> 00:47:00.400
But we also wanted to
keep Angular flexible.

00:47:00.400 --> 00:47:02.440
So you can choose,
as developers,

00:47:02.440 --> 00:47:05.300
use our implementation,
you can write your own,

00:47:05.300 --> 00:47:07.570
or you can find
one of the options

00:47:07.570 --> 00:47:10.760
out there in our
growing ecosystem.

00:47:10.760 --> 00:47:13.420
So among the additions
we have in Angular,

00:47:13.420 --> 00:47:15.470
we now have Angular
material, which

00:47:15.470 --> 00:47:18.530
is a tool of beautiful
design UI components

00:47:18.530 --> 00:47:23.110
so you can go from ZeroApp
to Beautiful App really fast.

00:47:23.110 --> 00:47:27.260
We have IET and PIs for your
internationalization needs.

00:47:27.260 --> 00:47:29.590
We brought a
powerful forms module

00:47:29.590 --> 00:47:34.570
for quickly developing user
input forms with validation.

00:47:34.570 --> 00:47:37.900
We have animations so that
your apps look and respond

00:47:37.900 --> 00:47:41.150
with style, and users
will enjoy using them.

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:43.510
And last, we have
ngUpgrade, which

00:47:43.510 --> 00:47:46.490
allows you to mix and match
old and new Angular components

00:47:46.490 --> 00:47:48.290
in the same application.

00:47:48.290 --> 00:47:50.680
So if you're one of the millions
of Angular 1 developers,

00:47:50.680 --> 00:47:54.740
you can migrate
at your own pace.

00:47:54.740 --> 00:47:57.970
So I've talked about the
building blocks of Angular.

00:47:57.970 --> 00:48:02.030
What about all the other places
that you need your apps to run?

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:05.320
First, Angular is great
for progressive web apps.

00:48:05.320 --> 00:48:08.200
We have a full talk from
developer advocate Stephen

00:48:08.200 --> 00:48:12.310
Fluin on this in the mobile
web track later today.

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:15.100
And for many consumer
apps, an app store presence

00:48:15.100 --> 00:48:16.220
is essential.

00:48:16.220 --> 00:48:19.600
So we've partnered with
Ionic and with Onsen UI, two

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.060
solutions that let you use
all of the goodness of web

00:48:22.060 --> 00:48:24.220
technologies, but
then package that up

00:48:24.220 --> 00:48:26.860
for the app store presence.

00:48:26.860 --> 00:48:29.780
If you prefer Native,
Telerik's NativeScript

00:48:29.780 --> 00:48:32.590
works by swapping out our
renderer for one that can

00:48:32.590 --> 00:48:34.990
render to a native mobile OS.

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:37.260
And this is possible
because of Angular's Dom

00:48:37.260 --> 00:48:39.010
independent renderer.

00:48:39.010 --> 00:48:42.760
Finally, for the desktop,
with GitHub's electron,

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:44.720
you can build in Angular
and take advantage

00:48:44.720 --> 00:48:47.140
of all the machine resources.

00:48:47.140 --> 00:48:51.650
If you've used VS code,
that's an electron app.

00:48:51.650 --> 00:48:55.040
So as with native mobile,
there are more places

00:48:55.040 --> 00:48:56.510
where there is no Dom.

00:48:56.510 --> 00:48:59.030
And we wanted Angular
to run there to you.

00:48:59.030 --> 00:49:02.090
So Angular now includes
server side rendering,

00:49:02.090 --> 00:49:06.800
so that the server can
render our component's view.

00:49:06.800 --> 00:49:10.400
This currently works in
Node and asp.net today,

00:49:10.400 --> 00:49:14.180
and the new Angular can
deploy to many platforms.

00:49:14.180 --> 00:49:16.670
So I've talked about the
building blocks of Angular

00:49:16.670 --> 00:49:18.870
and where your apps can run.

00:49:18.870 --> 00:49:23.190
But what about the tools
that you use as a developer?

00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:25.040
You can write an Angular
application using

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:28.040
plain ES5 or ES6 JavaScript.

00:49:28.040 --> 00:49:29.480
But we think that
most developers

00:49:29.480 --> 00:49:31.430
will want to use TypeScript.

00:49:31.430 --> 00:49:32.960
We like TypeScript
because it makes

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:34.790
it a lot easier
to write and think

00:49:34.790 --> 00:49:37.730
about Angular applications.

00:49:37.730 --> 00:49:41.370
We actually used TypeScript
to write Angular ourselves.

00:49:41.370 --> 00:49:43.790
And I would love to tell you
the beautiful engineering

00:49:43.790 --> 00:49:46.520
story that happened when
the love between our two

00:49:46.520 --> 00:49:48.950
open source projects at
Microsoft and at Google

00:49:48.950 --> 00:49:51.260
came together, but
I'm going to save that

00:49:51.260 --> 00:49:54.410
for our TypeScript
in Angular talk

00:49:54.410 --> 00:49:56.930
this afternoon, which
we are co-presenting

00:49:56.930 --> 00:50:01.010
in Chinese and in English, with
Microsoft engineer [CHINESE],

00:50:01.010 --> 00:50:03.350
from the TypeScript team.

00:50:03.350 --> 00:50:08.660
So why did Angular adopt
TypeScript for our own code?

00:50:08.660 --> 00:50:12.320
First, we could write
code and find beds faster.

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:14.420
The readability of
our code in TypeScript

00:50:14.420 --> 00:50:16.230
was greatly improved.

00:50:16.230 --> 00:50:18.830
And this was critical because
we had many engineers working

00:50:18.830 --> 00:50:21.050
together in many different
parts of the framework,

00:50:21.050 --> 00:50:23.900
and they needed to
quickly understand what

00:50:23.900 --> 00:50:25.280
the other engineers had done.

00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:28.556
They found they could
collaborate much more easily.

00:50:28.556 --> 00:50:29.930
And we found that
we could easily

00:50:29.930 --> 00:50:33.192
build much better
tooling, like Angular CLI.

00:50:36.110 --> 00:50:40.070
So with Angular's command line
interface, you can type ngnew

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:42.110
and we'll create all
the scaffolding and all

00:50:42.110 --> 00:50:44.101
the boilerplate
plate for you, so

00:50:44.101 --> 00:50:46.100
that when finally these
commands finish running,

00:50:46.100 --> 00:50:49.280
you can simply type ngsurf.

00:50:49.280 --> 00:50:51.950
Then you move over
to your local browser

00:50:51.950 --> 00:50:55.730
and your app will magically
be there, fully functional,

00:50:55.730 --> 00:50:58.850
so that you can focus
on application logic,

00:50:58.850 --> 00:51:02.390
not on the boilerplate plate.

00:51:02.390 --> 00:51:04.370
The CLI is one way
that we're investing

00:51:04.370 --> 00:51:08.060
in tooling, to make it easier
for you to write Angular code.

00:51:08.060 --> 00:51:12.410
We also provide Protractor,
which enables full end

00:51:12.410 --> 00:51:15.140
to end testing.

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:22.400
Angular and also works great
with your favorite IDE,

00:51:22.400 --> 00:51:27.550
and will give you helpful error
messaging and refactoring tips.

00:51:27.550 --> 00:51:30.860
Last, our partners at
Rangel.io have built

00:51:30.860 --> 00:51:33.500
a tool called Angular Augury.

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:36.350
Augury gives you real time
insight into performance

00:51:36.350 --> 00:51:37.920
and things like
routing in your app,

00:51:37.920 --> 00:51:40.250
so you can debug and see
what's happening in your app

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:42.020
much faster.

00:51:42.020 --> 00:51:44.810
This is just a taste of what
the new Angular can do today

00:51:44.810 --> 00:51:47.180
for mobile, desktop,
and the web,

00:51:47.180 --> 00:51:49.779
and how we improve
developer productivity.

